In article <1993Nov13.113051.28940@jarvis.csri.toronto.edu>,
David Jones <dej@eecg.toronto.edu> wrote:
>Why is RSA never used for a message body?  If RSA is cracked, then the IDEA
>key can be recovered, and the whole message falls.  Is it just a matter of
>speed?  (i.e. RSA is slow)

RSA is really slow for big amount of data. RSA  is dealing with big integer
numbers (generally about 1024 bits each) when IDEA work on 64 bits of data.
I think RSA generate also a much long ciphertext.

RSA is considered more secure  than either IDEA  and DES and far from being
broken.


